Jul 25 2005	Eh	Is the Mercer a nice hotel? Absolutely. Is it one of the top hotels in the city? Not even close. Presumably you are shelling out such high prices for the location and the scene in the lobby (if you're into that sort of thing). But for such high prices the Mercer simply does not hold up in comparison with other NYC hotels. The rooms are nice albeit fairly nondescript. I honestly can't really put my finger on what I don't like about the Mercer. I've stayed there a few times so I'm not going to let the one time somebody knocked on the door when the privacy sign was up really influence my opinion, nor will I worry about the occasional snooty staff member--this happens everyhwere and is usually just an isolated incident. I just think for the money you are spending you are much better off at the Ritz-Carleton, the Mark, or the FourSeasons. If you are that desperate for location, then yes, the Mercer is outstanding. Otherwise, go spend your money elsewhere.	
Jun 22 2005	Ruined for LIfe!	My husband and I stayed at the Mercer on our wedding night, and it was amazing. Since we were flying out early the next morning we only booked a Loft Studio. We were upgraded complimentary to the penthouse suite, and there was a bottle of Veuve waiting for us. This place is so chic and impeccable -- the sheets were plush, a soak in the giant tub so luxurious, the decor slick and gorgeous. We're spoiled for life, as nothing will ever seem as cool as this place. Even though we live in nearby Tribeca, we'll be back for our one year anniversary weekend!	
Jun 14 2005	The most comfortable hotel room ever	My husband and I loved the Mercer because of its location and because of the comfort of the room. Although the decor was a little bland (we know it's supposed to be minimalist), the room was cozy and comfortable. The linens had a high thread count (higher than other hotels that state their linens have a high thread count). The bathrobes and slippers were fabulous. Incredibly soft. Even the bath amenities from Face Stockholm were wonderful. The Vitamin A body lotion and the bath soap were the best. We did not have a bathtub, however. You have to book a more deluxe room for that. The welcome cookies were delicious and flower vase a nice touch. We did not get to interact very much with the staff because we were so busy, but they were all welcoming and attentive. My husband saw Ashley Olsen in the lobby. I missed her, however, because I am like Dana Scully in the X-Files and always miss the sightings. The location was great because it is in the middle of SoHo. My husband brought back pastries and coffee from Balthazar in the mornings. However, the last morning we ordered room service and it was very good. The hotel is also very close to the subway. The reason I did not rate it &quot;excellent&quot; is because of the room decor, lack of bathtub in a basic room, and lack of spa/pool in the hotel (although I believe guests have access to a local health club). Those amenities would have made the hotel perfect (for me). Otherwise, it is a great place to stay in New York and worth the money.	
